article.description:
Deanna Nolan scored 16 points to lead the Detroit
Shock over Phoenix 80-72 Saturday night, snapping the Mercury's four-game winning streak.
article.headline: Shock snap Mercury's 4-game win streak
article.linkText: Mercury falling: Shock cool off Phoenix 80-72
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Deanna Nolan scored 16 points to lead the Detroit
Shock over Phoenix 80-72 Saturday night, snapping the Mercury's
four-game winning streak.

Nolan hit a 17-footer with 1:33 left to give Detroit a 70-69
lead, then made six straight free throws in the final 51 seconds.
The Shock outscored Phoenix 15-7 over the last three minutes.

As a team, Detroit made 10 consecutive free throws in the final
1:10.

"If we are going to win on free throws down the stretch, the
right person was going to shoot them and that would be Deanna
Nolan," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said.

Penny Taylor scored 23 points to lead the Mercury (16-14), who
had won eight of nine and remained in fourth place in the Western
Conference. Diana Taurasi added 19.

"We couldn't get stops down the stretch," Phoenix coach Carrie
Graf said. "And we were patchy defensively and patchy on the
boards. We never really got into our offensive flow."

Ruth Riley had 15 points and Merlakia Jones 14 for the Shock,
who had lost their last two and four of five.

Detroit (15-17) played without leading scorer Swin Cash after
she injured her left knee in a collision with Phoenix's Nikki
McCray with 9:18 left in the first half. Cash came into the game
averaging 16.9 points, 6.7 rebounds and 4.4 assists. She was
carried off the floor and later was seen on crutches with her leg
immobilized.

"With Swin going down we got a little mentally fried there for
a while and threw the ball all over the gym," Laimbeer said. "But
we hung together and showed heart."

Detroit led 29-28 at halftime.
